Welcome to the=C2=A01,252=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined=
 us since our last Monday post! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=
=A0176,385 smart, curious folks by subscribing here:=20
=F0=9F=8E=A7=C2=A0 For the audio version, subscribe on Spotify [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/39d17735-ede6-466a-81c5-fa8d845cd405?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] or=C2=A0Apple Podcasts [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/c5c4ac0c-7497-44f8-ab07-05c13fff600c?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (later this w=
eek)
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Tuesday!=C2=A0This post is coming to you a a day late because it=E2=
=80=99s the longest I=E2=80=99ve essay I=E2=80=99ve ever written about the =
most complex subject I=E2=80=99ve ever written about.=20
There have been many times in Not Boring=E2=80=99s brief history when I=E2=
=80=99ve realized just how lucky I am to get to write for an audience of sm=
art, curious nerds like you. It takes a special kind of nerd to read multi-=
thousand word deep dives on topics ranging from blockchains to robots week =
after week. One of those times that stands out in my memory was in June 202=
1, when Jill Gunter [ https://substack.com/redirect/6a53bf10-f26d-4a72-b811=
-5cf3ed175322?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] and I wrote a piece on Zero-Knowledge Proofs called, creatively, Ze=
ro Knowledge [ https://substack.com/redirect/2a8263e1-b10e-4188-8a17-71e29a=
368319?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
=2E=C2=A0
Zero-Knowledge Proofs are wonky. For the first thirty or so years of their =
lives, they existed only deep in the research labs of academic cryptographe=
rs. They involve math that I couldn=E2=80=99t begin to understand, let alon=
e explain, and when we wrote that piece, their use cases were still almost =
purely speculative. Despite that, and despite the fact that there were only=
 56,891 of us here at that time, Zero Knowledge has been viewed 113k times =
and was our most popular piece of the month by a landslide.=C2=A0
In the piece, we gave an overview of Zero-Knowledge Proofs, and predicted t=
hat you=E2=80=99d be hearing a lot more about them over the next five years=
=2E Fast-forward 17 months, and the zero-=
knowledge zeitgeist is upon us. Star=
kware, zkSync, Aztec, Espresso, ImmutableX, Polygon=E2=80=99s zkEVM, and Al=
eo are either live on mainnet or in various stages of testnets. If they hit=
 their timelines, Zero Knowledge Proofs could be one of the breakout techno=
logies of 2023.=C2=A0
Today, we=E2=80=99re going to go deep on one of the most promising companie=
s in the zero-knowledge space: Aleo [ https://substack.com/redirect/bdaa4a7=
5-3cd6-4200-882a-d509d4e1922e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Aleo is a L1 blockchain that uses zero-knowledge p=
roofs to let developers build private-by-default applications. Its develope=
rs view zk-powered blockchains as the third wave. First, there was Bitcoin.=
 Then, there was Ethereum. Now, there=E2=80=99s Aleo.=C2=A0=C2=A0
This essay is a Sponsored Deep Dive. While the piece is sponsored, these ar=
e all my real and genuine views =E2=80=93 there=E2=80=99s no perfect blockc=
hain; it=E2=80=99s all about making the right trade-offs to serve the targe=
t audience and use cases. I expect to write about other L1s and L2s, includ=
ing zk Rollups, in the future. I am a maximalist minimalist.=C2=A0
You can read more about how I choose which companies to do deep dives on, a=
nd how I write them here [ https://substack.com/redirect/64c33754-4b9c-4ec8=
-a14f-7c3e61a49f4f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ].
Please, please for the love of God note that this is not investment advice.=
 Aleo doesn=E2=80=99t have a token live, but it will at some point. When th=
at time comes: please do not look back at this piece as investment advice. =
I am a terrible trader. This is a sponsored piece. a16z, where I=E2=80=99m =
an advisor, is an investor in Aleo. I have no idea where Aleo Credits will =
be priced when trading starts. I=E2=80=99m just fascinated by the technolog=
y and the potential applications of zero-knowledge proofs.=C2=A0
K? Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Aleo: Can You Keep A Secret?=20
Imagine a Bizarro Internet that=E2=80=99s exactly like the internet you use=
 today except for one detail: everything you do, send, or store on this Biz=
arro Internet is totally public.=C2=A0
When you buy a new pair of underwear on Amazon, your purchase is posted to =
a website that anyone with the desire and some basic skills can search.
Your balance at Bank of America is right there, too, for anyone to see.=C2=
=A0
You saddle up to the online poker table only to realize that you can see ev=
eryone=E2=80=99s cards=E2=80=A6 and they can see yours. This game sucks.=C2=
=A0
You message your wife and tell her you=E2=80=99ll be up for dinner soon and=
, of course, anyone who wants to see that you messaged your wife can.=C2=A0
Before you forget, you schedule a doctor=E2=80=99s appointment to get that =
thing checked out, and fill out an intake form online and, you guessed it, =
now anyone can peep that form in all its gory detail.
This Bizarro Internet would be practically unusable for anything besides pu=
blic forums and showing off things that you don=E2=80=99t mind if other peo=
ple see.=C2=A0
This Bizarro Internet is web3 as it stands today.=C2=A0
For most of the applications built on web3 to date, that level of transpare=
ncy is fine, and even novel and good. If you own a CryptoPunk, you want peo=
ple to know that you own a CryptoPunk. If you=E2=80=99re trading on a DEX, =
you=E2=80=99re mostly fine with people knowing what you bought and when. If=
 you=E2=80=99re casting on Farcaster, you want that to be public anyway.=C2=
=A0
But that=E2=80=99s a bit circular. The web3 products built to date are almo=
st definitionally the ones for which privacy isn=E2=80=99t a big deal. Zoom=
 out to the broader internet, and you=E2=80=99ll find privacy at the core o=
f every product that touches money or personal information.=C2=A0
If web3 is going to grow beyond these early experiments, and if decentraliz=
ed networks are going to come to replace more centralized services, adding =
in a bit of privacy would be helpful.
That=E2=80=99s where Zero-Knowledge Proofs (ZKPs) come in.=C2=A0
A zero-knowledge proof is a type of cryptographic protocol that allows one =
party (the Prover) to prove to another party (the Verifier) that they know =
a certain piece of information, without revealing any information about the=
 actual content of that information.=C2=A0
ZKPs are a way to prove that you know something, own something, or have don=
e something without revealing any information about that something. They=E2=
=80=99re a valuable primacy primitive that were too theoretical and expensi=
ve for practical use until very recently.=C2=A0
As people survey the crypto wreckage, zero-knowledge proofs are a bright sp=
ot. Good bubbles leave infrastructure in their wake for the next wave to bu=
ild upon, and ZKPs seem to be a treasure in the bubble=E2=80=99s rubble.=C2=
=A0
Zero-knowledge proofs are both a generally useful tool, and a tool tailor-m=
ade to help avoid the kind of fraud perpetrated by FTX.=C2=A0
Under the charmingly awkward title Having a safe CEX [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/bc2ae92e-6ce3-478e-af15-34e18980856f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Vitalik sketched out some ideas a=
round a 2015 concept from Dan Boneh=E2=80=99s team at Stanford called Proof=
 of Solvency [ https://substack.com/redirect/35a658e1-b92e-469b-b3bc-ae840b=
efa4e8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
, a way for centralized exchanges to prove that they have the funds to pay =
back their depositors without revealing any sensitive or proprietary inform=
ation.=C2=A0
At the core of the proposed architecture sit zkSNARKs (short for Zero-Knowl=
edge Succinct Non-Interactive Argument of Knowledge), a specific type of ZK=
P. This is how Vitalik introduced ZK-SNARKs:=C2=A0
ZK-SNARKs are a powerful technology. ZK-SNARKs may be to cryptography what =
transformers [ https://substack.com/redirect/849eed8c-a277-485f-aead-6ddbac=
60ce46?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 are to AI: a general-purpose technology that is so powerful that it will c=
ompletely steamroll a whole bunch of application-specific techniques for a =
whole bunch of problems that were developed in the decades prior.
One more time for those in the back: =E2=80=9CZK-SNARKs may be to cryptogra=
phy what transformers are to AI.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a big statement. If you=E2=80=99ve been living under a rock,=
 there=E2=80=99s something of an AI renaissance underfoot. At the heart of =
all of the insane progress being made is a new architecture: transformers. =
(Anton [ https://substack.com/redirect/e26640d7-ae6f-4624-969a-03dbf4111571=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] expla=
ins here [ https://substack.com/redirect/24c1d11b-95cb-40f0-81a5-4192acacec=
90?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ])
For blockchains specifically, ZKPs have two useful applications: scalabilit=
y and privacy.
Together, those features mean that ZKPs let blockchains approach the perfor=
mance of centralized services, and exceed their security and privacy, while=
 maintaining the benefits of decentralization.=C2=A0
There are no free lunches, of course, and that comes with a trade-off. Here=
, the biggest trade-off is the cost of privacy. It=E2=80=99s historically b=
een more expensive to generate a ZKP than to just run the computation nativ=
ely, as ZKPs require more complex and computationally expensive mathematica=
l operations, and because they rely on more specialized hardware.=C2=A0
By building a private-by-default L1, Aleo is making the bet that there=E2=
=80=99s enough demand from developers who are willing to pay a higher cost =
to build privacy into their applications, until they can shrink the cost. T=
he team is working to grow demand by =E2=80=9Ccommoditizing its complement,=
=E2=80=9D specifically hardware optimized to solve zero-knowledge proofs qu=
ickly and cheaply.=C2=A0
ZKPs are simultaneously incredibly complex to understand at a technical lev=
el (like, way beyond my abilities) and simple to understand at the usefulne=
ss level. They mean faster blockchains and applications that are open and p=
rivate. As a testament to their flexibility, zero-knowledge proofs are invo=
ked as a solution to both too little transparency (i.e. FTX =E2=86=92 Proof=
 of Solvency) and too much transparency (i.e. the fact that, without them, =
everyone knows your full on-chain balance and transaction history).=C2=A0
Zero-knowledge proofs will play a major role in the future of crypto, and p=
otentially, in the future of the internet. They were really hard to figure =
out, but now that they have been, they provide solutions that are strictly =
superior to the alternatives. How, exactly, they=E2=80=99ll be implemented =
is still up for debate.=C2=A0
One approach is to build zkRollups on top of existing L1 blockchains, like =
Ethereum. Leading players like Matter Labs (zkSync [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/7c2ef4ed-c2d5-4343-8b09-ed322493ff18?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]), Starkware [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/2b5601ca-5b1b-4ad2-b393-c3fb39706f5f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and Aztec [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/3b5acdb9-3f57-4876-98f7-94ac3f5d968f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] are taking this approach.=C2=A0
Another is to start from scratch and build new L1s with scaling and privacy=
 baked in at the base layer. That=E2=80=99s what Aleo [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/bdaa4a75-3cd6-4200-882a-d509d4e1922e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is doing.
Aleo was initially conceived as an L2 on Ethereum, but ZKPs on Ethereum are=
 larger =E2=80=93 they have to consume the full state of the application =
=E2=80=93 and Ethereum doesn=E2=80=99t support SNARK-friendly primitives =
=E2=80=93 hash functions and elliptic curves =E2=80=93 so the team rewrote =
the plan and decided to build its own L1 in order to deliver cheaper ZKPs.=
=C2=A0
Aleo is taking the most radical approach to building a zero-knowledge-based=
 blockchain from the ground up. Instead of building an EVM-compatible chain=
 on which developers can build apps in the familiar Solidity programming la=
nguage, it created its own virtual machine, snarkVM, and programming langua=
ge, Leo. Instead of relying on existing consensus mechanisms like Proof of =
Work (PoW) or Proof of Stake (PoS), it uses a combo of both, with a useful =
tweak on PoW called Proof of Succinct Work. The result should be ZKPs that =
are far cheaper on Aleo than they could be on top of Ethereum.=C2=A0
The bet it=E2=80=99s making is that developers will be willing to learn new=
 tricks in order to acquire scaling and privacy superpowers.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a bet that requires you to believe that not only will ZKPs be =
a nice feature, but that they=E2=80=99re foundational to a third way to bui=
ld blockchains:=C2=A0
Wave 1: Bitcoin
Wave 2: Ethereum
Wave 3: Aleo
Understanding why Aleo is making that bet is a great way to explore the det=
ails and implications of zero-knowledge proof technology. So today, we=E2=
=80=99ll go deep on zero-knowledge, Aleo, and the future of the internet:=
=C2=A0
Zero-Knowledge Refresher
Zero Knowledge, Many Applications=C2=A0
From Berkeley to Blockchain
DIZK & Zexe
Aleo: Private by Default
How Aleo Works
Commoditize Your Complements: AleoBFT & ZPrize
The Zero-Knowledge Landscape
Aleonomics=C2=A0
Risks & Regulation
The Decade of Zero Knowledge
Now it=E2=80=99s time to melt our brains a little bit by diving back into z=
ero-knowledge proofs, just in case you=E2=80=99ve gotten a little rusty sin=
ce Jill and I wrote about them twenty months ago.=C2=A0
Zero-Knowledge Refresher
Zero-knowledge proofs are a fancy bit of cryptography that allows one party=
 (the Prover) to prove to another party (the Verifier) that it knows someth=
ing, without revealing any information about that thing. They let someone p=
rove that they know a secret without giving up any information about that s=
ecret.
Those secrets can take many forms, from passwords to positions on a Battles=
hip board to dollars in a bank account. In Zero Knowledge [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/2a8263e1-b10e-4188-8a17-71e29a368319?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Jill and I used a toy exampl=
e: me proving that I have enough money to lease an apartment without giving=
 the real estate agent my bank records and financial history.=C2=A0
That ZKP box in the image is doing a lot of work. What=E2=80=99s going on i=
n there?=C2=A0
There are a bunch of different ways to explain how ZKPs work without going =
into the =E2=80=9Cmoon math.=E2=80=9D In Zero Knowledge, we used the =E2=80=
=9CColor Blind Friend=E2=80=9D example.=C2=A0
My color blind friend and I are looking at balls on a table that are identi=
cal except that one is red and the other green. He is not sure that he beli=
eves me when I tell him they are two different colors. We decide to establi=
sh that they are, in fact, different colors by playing a game:=C2=A0
I give him the two balls to hide behind his back.=C2=A0
He takes one ball out and shows it to me.=C2=A0
Then he puts this ball back behind his back, withdraws his hand again, show=
s me a ball and asks, =E2=80=9CDid I switch the balls?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
If we repeat this game enough times, and if I answer correctly every time, =
then I will demonstrate to him that the balls are almost certainly two diff=
erent colors. Importantly, here, I have proven this to him without revealin=
g any other information. Perhaps frustratingly for him, he still doesn=E2=
=80=99t know which ball is red and which ball is green.
For much, much more detail on Zero-Knowledge Proofs, including another expl=
anation, an overview of potential applications, the riveting adventures of =
Howard and Alex, Aleo details including consensus, economics, and progress,=
 how Aleo is commoditizing its complement, risks, regulation, and so much m=
ore=E2=80=A6=20
Thanks as always to Dan for editing, to Alex, Howard, Daniel, Drew, and Ali=
 for input on the piece, and to Jill for introducing me to the wonderful wo=
rld of ZKPs.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today! See you Friday for the most optimistic Weekly=
 Dose yet, and on Monday for my last essay of 2022!=20
Thanks for reading,=20
