4040; text-decoration: underline;">here</a><span>)</span></p><p style=3D"co=
lor: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><spa=
n>For blockchains specifically, ZKPs have two useful applications: </span><=
strong>scalability</strong><span> and </span><strong>privacy.</strong></p><=
p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 =
20px 0;"><span>Together, those features mean that </span><strong>ZKPs let b=
lockchains approach the performance of centralized services, and exceed the=
ir security and privacy, while maintaining the benefits of decentralization=
=2E</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p sty=
le=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">There are no free lunches, of co=
urse, and that comes with a trade-off. Here, the biggest trade-off is the c=
ost of privacy. It&#8217;s historically been more expensive to generate a Z=
KP than to just run the computation natively, as ZKPs require more complex =
and computationally expensive mathematical operations, and because they rel=
y on more specialized hardware.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">By building a private-by=
-default L1, Aleo is making the bet that there&#8217;s enough demand from d=
evelopers who are willing to pay a higher cost to build privacy into their =
applications, until they can shrink the cost. The team is working to grow d=
emand by &#8220;commoditizing its complement,&#8221; specifically hardware =
optimized to solve zero-knowledge proofs quickly and cheaply.&#160;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;"><span>ZKPs are simultaneously incredibly complex to understand at a t=
echnical level (like, way beyond my abilities) and simple to understand at =
the usefulness level. They mean faster blockchains and applications that ar=
e open </span><em>and</em><span> private. As a testament to their flexibili=
ty, zero-knowledge proofs are invoked as a solution to both too </span><em>=
little</em><span> transparency (i.e. FTX &#8594; Proof of Solvency) and too=
 </span><em>much </em><span>transparency (i.e. the fact that, without them,=
 everyone knows your full on-chain balance and transaction history).&#160;<=
/span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;">Zero-knowledge proofs will play a major role in the fut=
ure of crypto, and potentially, in the future of the internet. They were re=
ally hard to figure out, but now that they have been, they provide solution=
s that are strictly superior to the alternatives. How, exactly, they&#8217;=
ll be implemented is still up for debate.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #4040=
40; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>One appr=
oach is to build zkRollups on top of existing L1 blockchains, like Ethereum=
=2E Leading players like Matter Labs (</s=
pan><a href=3D"https://substack.com/=
